cs.NI, cs.IT, cs.MA, cs.SY, cs.MM

Reasoning: 
1. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) - The paper focuses on radio resource and mobility management in 5G ultra-dense networks, which falls under the domain of networking and internet architecture. 
2. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper uses a lognormal K-factor model and the multivariate Fox H-function to derive a closed-form expression for the XLOS service probability, which involves information theory concepts. 
3. cs.MA (Multi-Agent Systems) - The paper deals with the management of multiple agents (i.e., user equipment and radio nodes) in a network, which is a core topic in multi-agent systems. 
4. cs.SY (Systems and Control) - The paper proposes a new performance indicator (XLOS service probability) and develops a routine to automate the definition of the underlying Mellin-Barnes contour, which involves systems and control concepts. 
5. cs.MM (Multimedia) - Although not the primary focus, the paper mentions the use of Monte-Carlo simulations to underpin the numerical results, which is a common technique in multimedia research.
